Executive Summary

Recent advances in Large Language Model (LLM)-based fact-checking systems have introduced a transformative paradox into the global verification ecosystem: namely, that a sufficiently advanced fact-checker increasingly requires independent fact-checking proportional to its own confidence score. This phenomenon — formally designated Recursive Verification Inflation (RVI) — threatens to destabilize traditional trust architectures by introducing infinite audit recursion into ordinary epistemic workflows.

This white paper presents the Recursive Epistemic Infrastructure for Autonomous Fact-Checking Validation (REIFAV), a scalable framework intended to verify the outputs of AI fact-checkers through a hierarchy of progressively more skeptical fact-checkers, culminating in a ceremonial human disclaimer appended at the bottom of every page.

The proposed framework establishes a seven-layer verification cascade in which each verifier is itself verified by a supervisory verifier operating under reduced certainty constraints. Preliminary simulations indicate that while factual confidence decreases asymptotically toward zero, perceived institutional rigor increases by approximately 480%.

Key findings include:

* AI fact-checkers become most trustworthy immediately before producing any claims.
* Human oversight remains critical as a symbolic artifact.
* Footnotes longer than the original document improve public confidence by 63%.
* The phrase “independently verified” no longer possesses operational meaning under recursive conditions.

The report concludes that the optimal fact-checking environment is one in which no statement is ever fully accepted, rejected, or completed.

