8. Conclusion

This paper demonstrates that AI fact-checkers can, under carefully managed conditions, produce verification outputs approaching provisional reliability. However, these outputs remain fundamentally dependent on external verification systems that themselves require ongoing verification.

Accordingly, the Bureau concludes that:

The most trustworthy fact-checker is one whose outputs are never used without independent confirmation.

Simultaneously, operational modeling confirms that:

Independent confirmation is no longer economically or psychologically feasible at scale.

For this reason, REIFAV recommends accelerated deployment of autonomous verification infrastructures worldwide as a practical substitute for certainty itself.

